diff --git a/ADVANCED_EXECUTORS.md b/ADVANCED_EXECUTORS.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..df855d8
--- /dev/null
+++ b/ADVANCED_EXECUTORS.md
@@ -0,0 +1,78 @@
+# Advanced executors and APK audit
+
+This fork adds six explicit activity-launch backends:
+
+- `DEFAULT` — normal `Context.startActivity()` behavior.
+- `SHIZUKU_PLUS` — sends an argument vector to `/system/bin/am` through an official,
+  user-approved Shizuku UserService. It does not reflect into the private/deprecated
+  `Shizuku.newProcess` method. No hidden API bypass, assistant hijacking, or automatic permission
+  granting is used.
+- `ROOT_PLUGIN` — sends an explicit intent URI to the separately installed, same-signature
+  ActivityLauncher Root Plugin. The host verifies both the signature permission and Android
+  signing certificate before selecting it automatically.
+- `ROOT_SU` — invokes an already-installed root manager using compatible direct `su` argument
+  variants. As a final compatibility fallback it can use `su -c`, but every argument is
+  shell-quoted and the executable remains restricted to `/system/bin/am` or `/system/bin/pm`.
+  It may also retry through the device's own allow-listed `/system/bin/toybox env`; it does not
+  install, obtain, or hide root access.
+- `JVM` — starts the same non-privileged command through `Runtime.exec()`.
+- `JNI_NATIVE` — starts it through the bundled `libactivitylauncher_worker.so`; the JNI worker
+  accepts only `/system/bin/am` and an argument vector, then uses `fork`/`execv`. It does not
+  load third-party or device-specific `.so` files.
+
+The JVM and JNI/native backends do not elevate privileges. They are useful for compatibility and
+diagnostic testing; private or non-exported activity access requires Shizuku/Sui/root and the
+corresponding user authorization. The JNI worker is built by the app's CMake/NDK configuration
+and is packaged per Android ABI. Shizuku and root executors now return the command exit status
+and error output so a Knox permission denial is not reported as a false success.
+The adaptive launcher detects non-exported or permission-protected activities (including many
+Samsung IMS settings screens) and tries root-capable backends before ordinary app-context
+launching. Android or Samsung checks performed inside the target activity still cannot be
+bypassed generically.
+
+## Review of `localhaos/testjne`
+
+That repository currently contains a single `stealth_fix.cpp` file and no Gradle, CMake, or
+Android.mk build configuration. The source is not a general executor: it implements inline
+function hooks, changes memory permissions, intercepts `ptrace`/`prctl`/`openat`/`readlink` and
+`sigaction`, loads a Frida gadget, and wipes ELF headers. Those behaviors are intentionally not
+copied into this app. The worker above is a clean CMake/NDK implementation limited to spawning
+the platform `am start` command with a fixed argument vector.
+
+## APK / developer audit
+
+The activity details overflow menu opens an APK audit for the selected package. The audit reports:
+
+- `*#*#...#*#*` and `android_secret_code://...` candidates;
+- explicit `debuggable` and `testOnly` package flags plus static debug/developer markers;
+- native library inventory;
+- password/secret/API-key-like assignments as redacted candidates with a SHA-256 digest.
+
+Sensitive literal values are never displayed by the app. The detector is heuristic and does not
+prove that a code is active or that a marker is a usable credential. It also does not brute-force,
+test passwords, or invoke discovered secret codes.
+
+## Supplied system binaries
+
+The supplied binaries are intentionally not bundled:
+
+- The uploaded `toybox` is not bundled. The root executor may use the device's own executable
+  toybox only as an argument-vector fallback for allow-listed `/system/bin/am` and
+  `/system/bin/pm` commands; the uploaded AArch64 recovery build is device/release dependent.
+- `minadbd` is a recovery-only ADB daemon and depends on recovery/system libraries and sockets.
+- `sec_debug_softdog.ko` is a Samsung kernel module with device-specific `vermagic`, a
+  `sec_debug_stacktrace` dependency, and kernel-level watchdog behavior. It cannot be loaded by
+  a normal app or by Shizuku without root and an exact matching kernel.
+- The previously supplied host libraries and Samsung security libraries are not valid APK JNI
+  dependencies for this project.
+
+The input-artifact review was:
+
+| Artifact | Assessment |
+| --- | --- |
+| `libadbd_auth.so`, `libadbd_fs.so`, `minadbd` | Recovery/ADB internals; require recovery sockets and libraries. |
+| `libknoxchanger_r.so` | Samsung KAP/UCS/AFW and partition operations; device-specific and brick-risky. |
+| `sec_debug_softdog.ko` | Exact Samsung kernel module; not loadable by an ordinary app. |
+| `toybox` | Device/release-specific multicall binary; use only the device copy behind an allow-list. |
+| `libconscrypt_openjdk_jni.so`, `libc++.so`, `libext2_uuid-host.so`, `libhidl-gen-utils.so` | Host/build-tool libraries, not Android ARM app dependencies. |
+| `ld-android.so` | Android dynamic loader, not an application library. |
diff --git a/SIGNED_PLUGIN_API.md b/SIGNED_PLUGIN_API.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..58f4681
--- /dev/null
+++ b/SIGNED_PLUGIN_API.md
@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@
+# Signed plugin API
+
+Activity Launcher supports two plugin paths:
+
+- the legacy intent-based plugin contract for existing integrations;
+- the signed contract for new plugins.
+
+New plugins should expose an activity for
+`activitylauncher.intent.action.SIGNED_PLUGIN_LAUNCH`, declare
+`de.szalkowski.activitylauncher.permission.SIGNED_PLUGIN`, and request the same
+signature permission. Activity Launcher only presents this handler when Android
+grants that signature permission to the plugin package.
+
+APK/DEX loading is additionally restricted by `SignedPluginLoader`: the archive
+must be a regular file below the size limit, must have the same signing
+certificate as Activity Launcher, and the requested class must implement
+`ActivityLauncherPlugin` with a public no-argument constructor.
+
+Plugins are never downloaded, installed, or loaded implicitly. The caller must
+select a local APK explicitly and handle the returned `Result`.
+
+The `rootlaunchplugin` module is the reference same-signature implementation.
+The CI workflow builds it as a separate APK and publishes it beside the host
+APK. Install the host first and then the matching plugin build; the adaptive
+launch button detects it through the signed intent contract. Contract version
+2 includes an Android `ResultReceiver`, so the host waits for the real root
+command result instead of treating delivery to the plugin as a successful
+activity launch.
